export const AUDIT_CHECKLIST_MD = "# E-E-A-T Audit Checklist\n\n**The instrument task A1 runs.** Work through it per client site each quarter. Every **Gap** becomes a line in the quarter's work queue (task A2 triages them — **YMYL-critical gaps first**). Each item points to the task that fixes it and the client input you'll need to request.\n\n> Compiled from the E-E-A-T Team Briefing: the four pillars' buildable signals, the Trust 5-point list, the \"what good looks like\" exemplars, and the anonymized-audit red flags.\n\n## How to score\n\nMark each item in the **Score** column:\n\n| Mark | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| **P** | Pass — the signal is present and verifiable |\n| **G** | Gap — missing, weak, or unverifiable → goes to the work queue |\n| **N** | N/A — genuinely doesn't apply to this client (note why) |\n\n**YMYL?** = a `★` means a gap here is YMYL-critical (cost, accreditation, outcomes, licensing, health, or \"who is responsible\") and is triaged **first** in A2.\n**Fixed by** = the quarterly task that closes the gap (see `EEAT-Quarterly-Checklist.md`).\n**Needs from client** = the input to request (drives outreach task O1) if the gap is caused by missing material.\n\n---\n\n## 1. 60-second triage — instant red flags\n\nThe anonymized audit failed the trust test while passing the eye test. Run these first; any `G` here is YMYL-critical by definition.\n\n| # | Instant red flag — auto-fail if present | YMYL? | Score | Fixed by |\n|---|---|:---:|:---:|---|\n| 0.1 | No HTTPS, mixed content, or insecure forms | ★ | | TR1 |\n| 0.2 | No tuition / refund / outcomes disclosure anywhere | ★ | | TR3 |\n| 0.3 | No named, verifiable people — can't tell who is responsible | ★ | | TR2 |\n| 0.4 | No accreditor link / no proof the school is recognized | ★ | | B5 |\n| 0.5 | Stock photos or anonymous testimonials presented as real | ★ | | B1 / B4 |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Trust — the foundation (\"who is responsible, and can I verify it?\")\n\n| # | Audit item — what good looks like | YMYL? | Score | Fixed by | Needs from client |\n|---|---|:---:|:---:|---|---|\n| T.1 | HTTPS everywhere; no mixed content; forms submit securely | ★ | | TR1 | — |\n| T.2 | Real physical address shown and consistent across the site | | | TR2 | — |\n| T.3 | Working phone number present | | | TR2 | — |\n| T.4 | Named staff and an About / leadership page (real people) | ★ | | TR2 | (instructors helps) |\n| T.5 | Accreditation disclosed on-site | ★ | | TR3 | recognition |\n| T.6 | Licensing disclosed on-site | ★ | | TR3 | recognition |\n| T.7 | Tuition / cost disclosure — clear and findable | ★ | | TR3 | — |\n| T.8 | Refund policy disclosed | ★ | | TR3 | — |\n| T.9 | Complaint / grievance policy disclosed | | | TR3 | — |\n| T.10 | Outcomes disclosure (completion / placement / licensure rates) | ★ | | TR3 | outcomes |\n| T.11 | \"Last reviewed / updated\" dates on key pages | | | TR4 | — |\n| T.12 | Corrections policy present | | | TR4 | — |\n| T.13 | Privacy policy present and current | | | TR4 | — |\n| T.14 | Genuine reviews displayed on-site | | | TR5 | — |\n| T.15 | Reviews are responded to | | | TR5 | — |\n| T.16 | Active Google Business Profile with consistent NAP | | | TR5 | — |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Experience — \"we've actually done this\"\n\n| # | Audit item — what good looks like | YMYL? | Score | Fixed by | Needs from client |\n|---|---|:---:|:---:|---|---|\n| E.1 | Real, non-stock campus / classroom / clinic photography | | | B1 | photos |\n| E.2 | Actual student-work / before-after gallery, students named | | | B1 | photos |\n| E.3 | Named student / grad testimonials with photos | | | B4 | outcomes |\n| E.4 | Testimonials tied to a specific outcome (job, license, placement) | | | B4 / B3 | outcomes |\n| E.5 | Outcome / proof pages: named grads, jobs landed, licenses passed | ★ | | B3 | outcomes |\n| E.6 | First-hand externship / clinical-placement stories | | | B8 | story |\n| E.7 | Instructor field notes / real practitioner accounts | | | B8 | story / instructors |\n| E.8 | No stock imagery or anonymous quotes posing as real | ★ | | B1 / B4 | photos / outcomes |\n\n---\n\n## 4. Expertise — \"we know this\"\n\n> Caveat from the briefing: a rented byline does nothing — the expertise has to be self-evident in the content itself.\n\n| # | Audit item — what good looks like | YMYL? | Score | Fixed by | Needs from client |\n|---|---|:---:|:---:|---|---|\n| X.1 | Named instructors (not \"our expert faculty\") | | | B2 | instructors |\n| X.2 | Bios show real licenses / certifications | | | B2 | instructors |\n| X.3 | Credential is visible on the page, not just claimed | | | B2 | instructors |\n| X.4 | Program copy authored or reviewed by qualified staff (reviewer byline + date) | | | R1 / B2 | instructors |\n| X.5 | Accurate cert / license detail — correct exam names and requirements | ★ | | B7 | recognition |\n| X.6 | Pass-rate context accurate and current | ★ | | B7 | recognition / outcomes |\n| X.7 | Expertise is self-evident in the content (no empty/rented bylines) | | | R1 | instructors |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Authoritativeness — \"others recognize us\" (cannot be self-declared)\n\n| # | Audit item — what good looks like | YMYL? | Score | Fixed by | Needs from client |\n|---|---|:---:|:---:|---|---|\n| A.1 | Accreditor's own page lists and links the school (ABHES / COE / ACCSC) | ★ | | B5 | recognition |\n| A.2 | State / provincial recognition (US licensing boards; BC PTIB / EQA) | ★ | | B6 | recognition |\n| A.3 | Consistent entity across the web (stable NAP), active GBP, genuine reviews | | | TR5 | — |\n| A.4 | Credible third-party mentions / quality backlinks (local news, industry bodies, .edu) | | | — *(see note)* | recognition |\n\n> **Note on A.4:** Surfacing and verifying *existing* mentions/links fits the quarterly cycle, but *earning net-new* links is digital-PR work outside the ~8 hr/quarter \"what we handle\" scope. Log a gap here as a flag for a separate effort, not a quarterly build task.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Structured data quick-check (machines, not just people)\n\n> Schema where it earns its place — markup on a hollow page is still a hollow page. Only mark Pass if the underlying substance exists.\n\n| # | Audit item | Score | Fixed by | Needs from client |\n|---|---|:---:|---|---|\n| D.1 | Person schema on named instructors (with credentials) | | S1 | instructors |\n| D.2 | Organization + accreditation schema | | S2 | recognition |\n| D.3 | Review / aggregateRating schema where genuine reviews exist | | S3 | outcomes |\n| D.4 | EducationalOccupationalProgram / Course schema on program pages | | S4 | — |\n\n---\n\n## 7. Roll-up → hand to A2\n\nAfter scoring, tally and feed the quarter's queue:\n\n| Pillar | Items | Gaps (G) | YMYL-critical gaps (★ + G) |\n|---|---:|---:|---|\n| Triage red flags | 5 | | |\n| Trust | 16 | | |\n| Experience | 8 | | |\n| Expertise | 7 | | |\n| Authoritativeness | 4 | | |\n| Structured data | 4 | | |\n| **Total** | **44** | | |\n\n**Prioritization rule (A2):** YMYL-critical gaps first → remaining Trust gaps → the pillar with the most gaps → schema last. Then check the **Needs from client** column: any input that appears against an unfixable gap goes into the **O1 material request**. With abundant material, build tasks rotate across quarters (the ~8 hr/quarter budget is a floor on the highest-leverage work, not a cap on the backlog).\n";
